SIMPLE: malic
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Malic
<hw>Ma"lic</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>malum</ets> an
apple: cf. F. <ets>malique</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Chem.)</fld>
<def>Pertaining to, or obtained from, apples; <as>as, <ex>malic</ex>
acid</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Malic acid</b></col>, <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <cd>a hydroxy
acid (<chform>HO.CO.CH2.CH(OH).CO.OH</chform>) obtained from unripe
fruit (such as <prodby>green apples</prodby>, <prodby>currants</prodby>,
<prodby>tomatoes</prodby> or <prodby>cherries</prodby>) as a substance
which is sirupy or crystallized with difficulty, and has a strong but
pleasant sour taste. It is levorotatory or dextrorotatory according to
the temperature and concentration; the natural form is of L-
conformation. A synthetic variety is a derivative of succinic acid, but
as with most simple synthetic compounds, is a racemic mixture of isomers
and thus has no rotatory action on polarized light.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>malice</ent>⟦br⟧
